====Verb====
{{en-verb|clos|ing}}

# {{label|en|physical}} To remove a gap.
## To obstruct (an [[opening]]).
## To move so that an opening is closed.
##: {{ux|en|'''Close''' the door behind you when you leave.}}
##: {{ux|en|Jim was listening to headphones with his eyes '''closed'''.}}
##* {{w|Lord Byron}} (1788-1824)
##*: What deep wounds ever '''closed''' without a scar?
##* {{quote-book|year=1977|author={{w|Agatha Christie}}|part=2|chapter=2
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL472758W An Autobiography]
|passage=If I '''close''' my eyes I can see Marie today as I saw her then. Round, rosy face, snub nose, dark hair piled up in a chignon.}}
## To make (e.g. a gap) smaller.
##: {{ux|en|The runner in second place is '''closing''' the gap on the leader.}}
##: {{ux|en|to '''close''' the ranks of an army}}
## To grapple; to engage in close combat.
##* {{w|William H. Prescott}} (1796-1859)
##*: They boldly '''closed''' in a hand-to-hand contest.
# {{label|en|social}} To finish, to terminate.
## To put an [[end]] to; to conclude; to complete; to finish; to consummate.
##: {{ux|en|'''close''' the session; &emsp; to '''close''' a bargain; &emsp; to '''close''' a course of instruction}}
##* {{w|John Dryden}} (1631-1700)
##*: One frugal supper did our studies '''close'''.
## To come to an end.
##: {{ux|en|The debate '''closed''' at six o'clock.}}
## {{label|en|marketing}} To make a [[sale]].
## {{label|en|baseball|pitching}} To make the final outs, usually three, of a game.
##: {{ux|en|He has '''closed''' the last two games for his team.}}
## {{label|en|figurative|computing}} To terminate an [[application]], [[window]], [[file]] or [[database]] [[connection]], etc.
# To come or gather around; to enclose; to encompass; to confine.
#* Bible, {{w|Book of Jonah|Jonah}} ii. 5
#*: The depth '''closed''' me round about.
#* {{w|George Herbert}} (1593-1633)
#*: But now Thou dost Thyself immure and '''close''' / In some one corner of a feeble heart; / Where yet both Sinne and Satan, Thy old foes, / Do pinch and straiten Thee, and use much art / To gain Thy thirds' and little part.
